# No SPA-fallback 200-rewrite block here on purpose. A prior version of
# this file had rules like "/guides/* / 200" intended to fall back to the
# SPA shell for paths not covered by prerendering yet - but Cloudflare
# Pages applies _redirects rules BEFORE checking whether a matching static
# asset already exists, so every one of those wildcard rules was silently
# hijacking its own already-prerendered pages (e.g. /guides/bearded-dragon/,
# /encyclopedia/category/small-mammals/) and serving the fully-baked
# homepage's HTML in their place - confirmed live via curl showing the
# homepage's <title> and canonical on dozens of unrelated pages, caught by
# an Ahrefs crawl. This broke canonical/title/og-tags sitewide.
#
# Static assets are always served correctly with no rule needed here at
# all - every guide/encyclopedia/blog/static page is prerendered (see
# prerender.mjs), so Cloudflare finds and serves the real file directly.
# For the handful of routes with no static file (e.g. /donate/success,
# /donate/cancel after a Stripe redirect, or /pack/), Cloudflare's
# automatic 404.html handling serves a real 404 status - but since this is
# a client-side-routed SPA, React Router reads the actual browser URL on
# mount regardless of which HTML/status was initially served, so a real
# visitor's JS still loads and renders the correct page either way. Only
# a non-JS crawler hitting one of those exact few noindex routes would see
# a 404 instead of a soft 200 - an acceptable trade for not breaking SEO
# tags on every real, indexed page on the site.
